Date Subscripts

These should be disabled on mobile.

One reason I‚Äôm interested in the date subscript idea is that I already try to be consistent with commas to distinguish years from numbers which happen to fall in the range 1,000‚Äì2,100. (What about years whose number form wouldn‚Äôt have a comma, and they are ambiguous, like ‚Äò999‚Äô the number vs ‚Äò999 AD‚Äô? There aren‚Äôt many of those on Gwern.net so they‚Äôll just have to be marked up manually or possibly the regexp match made more complicated to match an AD/ BC suffix).

So hypothetically I can mark up years differently from numbers, and ranges as well.

A date ‚Äò1500‚Äô (which is not the number ‚Äò1,500‚Äô) can be subscripted 1500~524ya~ while a ‚Äò1,500‚Äô is ignored; and a date-range like ‚Äòthe third Swisso-Franco incursion ( 1549 ‚Äì 54 1603 421ya ) led to‚Ä¶‚Äô can be marked up as both a sub and superscript, say, like 1549--<sup>52</ sup>1603<sub>421ya</ sub> ‚Äîto tell you at a glance that this war lasted an epic half century half a millenium ago.

So it‚Äôd go:

  • single non-date number: nothing

  • single date number: subscript years-ago

    Ranges and years-ago are rounded like inflation, to keep them workable for large ones, like in archaeology or anthropology or evolution where you might have a 10 million year range 100 million years ago.

  • double non-date number range: superscript range

  • double date number: superscript range, subscript years-ago.

Test-cases for using subscripts to annotate dates with auto-generated time spans to avoid the ‚Å†‚Äòcontext collapse‚Äô or ‚Äòeternal present‚Äô problem ‚Å† as temporal intuitions seem to be breaking down.

WII was 1939 ‚Äì 6 1945 79ya , or more specifically, 1939-09-01 ‚Äì 6y 1945-09-02 79ya . The end of WWII was 1945 79ya . It is now 2025. It used to be 2009 15ya . Whereas in the year 1492 532ya , Columbus sailed the ocean blue. RIP Sir Thomas Browne ‚Å† ( 1605-10 ‚Äì 77y 1682-10 342ya ).

Hirohito reigned 1926 ‚Äì 63 1989 35ya . The first atomic bombing to surrender speech interval was 1945-08-06 ‚Äì 10d 1945-08-15 79ya . Then 1945-08-15 ‚Äì 2m 1945-10-09 79ya saw the new cabinet. In the 1900s, Neon Genesis Evangelion : 1995-10-04 ‚Äì 6m 1996-03-27 28ya , or sim 1995-10 ‚Äì 5m 1996-03 28ya .

There were 1,700‚Äì2,001 ships available for moe anthropomorphism. 999. 1. 55. 2. 2600. 0. 3-2-1-0. 2000s.

Mismatch

This is a span-level abstract inside a div collapse.

This is the rest of the collapse. We need this to check that mixing a span-inside-div works along with the usual div-inside-div approach to writing the abstracts for a collapse. When writing, you should make sure they match, of course, but you might have writing reasons to use a mixed span, or you might refactor and move things around, and what once matched no longer matches (and this would break things in hard-to-notice-or-debug ways). We do not test the div-inside-span mismatch case because it appears to be nearly impossible to write that in Pandoc Markdown in a way which doesn't yield horribly-broken HTML, so there is no need to handle it or test that case specially.

																// BOTTOM-UP METHOD
															
															 
															
																// given pass n in "from", compute pass n-1 in "to"
															
															
																static
																void propagate
																(DATATYPE 
																*from
																, DATATYPE 
																*to
																)
																{
															
															
																// for each money state...
															
															
																#pragma omp parallel for num_threads(THREADS)
															
															
																for
																(
																int a 
																=
																0
																; a 
																< THREADS
																; a
																++)
																{
															
															
																// distribute workload so that inner loop passes are approximately equal
															
															
																// f(x) = 2x  F(x) = x^2   = a/THREADS x = sqrt(a / THREADS)
															
															
																int low 
																=
																(
																int
																)
																(MONEY_LIMIT 
																* sqrtf
																((
																float
																)a 
																/ THREADS
																));
															
															
																int high 
																=
																(
																int
																)
																(MONEY_LIMIT 
																* sqrtf
																((a 
																+
																1.0
																f
																)
																/ THREADS
																));
															
															
																if
																(a 
																== THREADS 
																-
																1
																) high 
																= MONEY_LIMIT 
																+
																1
																;
																// precise upper border
															
															
																for
																(
																int m 
																= low
																; m 
																< high
																; m
																++)
																{
															
															      DATATYPE max_score 
																=
																0.0
																;
															
															
																// determine the bet that maximizes our expected earnings
															
															
																// to enable vectorization we break the loop into two so that each half only gets one branch of the conditional
															
															
																// DATATYPE winval = from[(m + b > MONEY_LIMIT) ? MONEY_LIMIT : (m + b)];
															
															
																int high_inner 
																=
																(m 
																+ m 
																> MONEY_LIMIT
																)
																?
																(MONEY_LIMIT 
																- m
																)
																: m
																;
															
															
																for
																(
																int b 
																=
																0
																; b 
																<= high_inner
																; b
																++)
																{
															
															        DATATYPE winval 
																= from
																[m 
																+ b
																];
															
															        DATATYPE loseval 
																= from
																[m 
																- b
																];
															
															        DATATYPE combined 
																= F
																(
																0.6
																)
																* winval 
																+ F
																(
																0.4
																)
																* loseval
																;
															
															        max_score 
																= F
																(fmax
																)(max_score
																, combined
																);
															
															
																}
															
															
																for
																(
																int b 
																= high_inner 
																+
																1
																; b 
																<= m
																; b
																++)
																{
															
															        DATATYPE winval 
																= from
																[MONEY_LIMIT
																];
															
															        DATATYPE loseval 
																= from
																[m 
																- b
																];
															
															        DATATYPE combined 
																= F
																(
																0.6
																)
																* winval 
																+ F
																(
																0.4
																)
																* loseval
																;
															
															        max_score 
																= F
																(fmax
																)(max_score
																, combined
																);
															
															
																}
															
															      to
																[m
																]
																= max_score
																;
															
															
																}
															
															
																}
															
															
																}
															
															 
															
																void method2
																()
																{
															
															  DATATYPE 
																*buf 
																= malloc
																(
																sizeof
																(DATATYPE
																)
																*
																(MONEY_LIMIT 
																+
																1
																));
															
															  DATATYPE 
																*buf_to 
																= malloc
																(
																sizeof
																(DATATYPE
																)
																*
																(MONEY_LIMIT 
																+
																1
																));
															
															
																// set up base case: making no bet, we have money of i
															
															
																for
																(
																int i 
																=
																0
																; i 
																<= MONEY_LIMIT

																]

																-
																1
																; i 
																>=
																0
																; i
																--)
																{
															
															    propagate

																, buf_to
																);
															
															    DATATYPE 
																*temp 
																= buf
																;
															
															    buf 
																= buf_to
																;
															
															    buf_to 
																= temp
																;
															
															
																}
															
															
																int best_bet 
																=
																0
																;
															
															  DATATYPE best_bet_score 
																=
																-
																1
																;
															
															
																for

																0

																(combined 
																> best_bet_score
																)
																{

																;
															
															      best_bet 
																= b
																;
															
															
																}
															
															
																}
															
															  printf

																 for expected total reward of

																);
															
															
																}

																def split_by_book(poems):
															
															  prev_gid 
																=
																-
																1
															
															  r 
																= []
															
															
																for entry 
																in poems:
															
															    gid 
																= entry[
																'gid']
															
															
																if gid 
																!= prev_gid:
															
															
																if prev_gid 
																!=
																-
																1
																and
																len(r) 
																>
																0:
															
															
																yield r
															
															        r 
																= []
															
															      prev_gid 
																= gid
															
															    r 
																+= [entry]
															
															
																if
																len(r) 
																>
																0:
															
															
																yield r
															
															 
															
																def split_by_transition(poems):
															
															  prev_line 
																=
																-
																2
															
															  r 
																= []
															
															
																for entry 
																in poems:
															
															    line 
																= entry[
																'line']
															
															
																if line 
																!= prev_line 
																+
																1:
															
															
																if prev_line 
																!=
																-
																2
																and
																len(r) 
																>
																0:
															
															
																yield r
															
															        r 
																= []
															
															    prev_line 
																= line
															
															    r 
																+= [entry]
															
															
																if
																len(r) 
																>
																0:
															
															
																yield r
															
															 
															
																def extract(entries):
															
															
																return
																'
																\n
																'.join(
																list(
																map(
																lambda x: x[
																's'], entries)))
															
															 
															
																def final(poems):
															
															
																for book 
																in split_by_book(poems):
															
															
																yield
																'<|endoftext|>'

																in split_by_transition(book):

																len(stanza) 
																>
																5:
															
															
																yield
																'
																\n
																'
															
															
																for entry 
																in stanza:
															
															          line 
																= entry[
																's'] 
																# {
															
															          line 
																= line.rstrip(
																'} ')
															
															
																yield line
															
															 
															
																def output(poems, fname):
															
															
																with
																open(fname, 
																"w") 
																as f:

															      f.write(line 
																+
																'
																\n
																')

‚Ä¶G. Geiger investigated the breeding-book of Dachshunds ‚Å† in Germany in 1973 51ya and found the scores better distributed than the data studied by Sacher, perhaps due to the 12-point system used as opposed to the 4-point system used in the pointer prize classes [ie. measurement error ‚Å† / range restruction]. He conducted a 3-level nested analysis of variance on 1,463 full-sub & half-sib progeny of 21 sires. In contrast to the earlier findings of Humphrey & Warner 1934 90ya , King 1954 70ya and Mahut 1958 66ya , his results showed maternal effects but no effect due to sex. The heritabilities are shown in Table 3 (Geiger 1973 51ya , cited in Pfleiderer-Hogner 1979 45ya ).

A second study of additive genetic variation in 1973 51ya came from the Army Dog Training Center in Solleftea, Sweden. C. Reuterwall and N. Ryman reported on their study of 958 German Shepherds from 29 sires. The 8 behavioral traits studied were labeled A-H:

  • Trait A was termed ‚ÄúAffability‚Äù (tested by having an unknown person confront the dog);

  • Trait B was termed ‚ÄúDisposition for Self Defense‚Äù (tested by having an unknown person attack the dog);

  • Trait C was termed ‚ÄúDisposition for Self Defense and Defense of Handler‚Äù (tested by having an unknown person attack the dog and handler);

  • Trait D was termed ‚ÄúDisposition for Fighting in a Playful Manner‚Äù (tested by asking the dog to fight for a sleeve or stick);

  • Trait E was termed ‚ÄúCourage‚Äù (tested by having a man-shaped figure approach the dog);

  • Trait F was termed ‚ÄúAbility to Meet with Sudden Strong Auditory Disturbance‚Äù (tested by firing shots at some distance and making a noise with tin cans just behind the dog);

  • Trait G was termed ‚ÄúDisposition for Forgetting Unpleasant Incidents‚Äù (tested by scaring the dog at a certain place and then asking the dog to pass the place again);

  • Trait H was termed ‚ÄúAdaptiveness to Different Situations and Environments‚Äù (tested by observations during the other parts of the test).

In contrast to Geiger‚Äôs findings, Reuterwall and Ryman reported statistically-significant ‚Å† differences between the sexes, males handling noise (Trait F) better and exhibiting more controlled defense (part of Trait C) and playful fighting (Trait D). Sex differences had also been noted by Humphrey & Warner 1934 90ya , King 1954 70ya and Mahut 1958 66ya . Reuterwall and Ryman noted that, in all 380 the traits studied, the additive genetic variation was small (Reuterwall & Ryman 1973 51ya ). The heritability estimates listed in Table 4 were reported by Willis based on the information found in Reuterwall and Ryman (Willis 1977 47ya ). It should be noted that the scores used by Reuterwall and Ryman were transformed and extremely complex. Some workers in Sweden today, working on the genetics of the breeding program at the Statens Hundskola, feel that the findings of Reuterwall and Ryman‚Äôs study are based on scores too complex to have much meaning (L. Falt 1982 42ya , personal communication).

Killing Rabbits

On Sunday after breakfast,
when the air is about halfway to ice,
the thin flutes of the mice are whistling in the chimney,
on Sunday after breakfast
to walk over fresh snow
to the cages.

Pull off the gloves for the rose feast.
Impale them on the fence
like freshly severed palms
and smoke through the door.
And then insert the hungry hand
and with smoke in your teeth utter sweet words,
caressing and gentle,
a touch of pity,
then a firm grab of the skin,
lifting it from the warm straw.

On Sunday after breakfast
sniff the ammonia.

For a while hold it head downwards,
watch the ears turning dark red,
gently stroke its back,
exhale, carry it off
and abruptly strike the back of its neck with the right hand.

Once more in your palm feel the effort
of a now useless leap,
feel a weight in your hand,
sweet taste on your palate,
hear the rabbits‚Äô heaven open
and fistfuls of fur falling from it.

Viennese blue,
Flemish giant ‚Å† ,
French lop-eared ‚Å† ,
Czech piebald,
and even the bastards of no matter what blood,
they all die equally swiftly
and soundlessly,

On Monday with blue under your eyes keep silent,
on Tuesday reflect on the fate of the world,
on Wednesday and Thursday
bring out the steam engine
and discover the stars,
on Friday think of others,
and especially of blue eyes,
all week long feel sorry for orphans
and admire flowers,
on Saturday step pink from your bath
and fall asleep on her lips.

On Sunday after breakfast
kill a rabbit.

1963 [from ‚Å†One Hundred Years of Slovak Literature: An Anthology ‚Å† , ed. Chrobakova 2000 ]

Link Icons

Link icons should follow the priority of: file type < domain < organization.

For example, a DeepMind paper hosted on Gwern.net should be assigned the ‚Å†DeepMind icon ‚Å† , not the Gwern.net ‚Äòùîä‚Äô icon nor a PDF icon. This is to make link icons as informative as possible: knowing a link is by or about DeepMind is far more informative‚Äîthe reader instantly knows it involves deep learning, and almost certainly deep reinforcement learning, of DeepMind‚Äôs particular house-style‚Äîthan knowing that knowing it‚Äôs a file which happens to be hosted on some domain (gwern.net), which is itself (usually) more informative than knowing it‚Äôs just some sort of PDF document (at who knows where by who knows whom about who knows what).

To display all link colors simultaneously, paste into JS browser console: Array . from( document . styleSheets) . forEach(styleSheet => { Array . from(styleSheet . cssRules) . forEach(rule => { if (rule . selectorText > "") rule . selectorText = rule . selectorText . replaceAll( ":hover" , "") ; }) ; }) ;

Unfortunately, I know of no particularly comprehensive lists of examples of mis-specified rewards/ unexpectedly bad proxy objective functions/ ‚Äúreward hacking‚Äù/ ‚Äúwireheading‚Äù/ ‚Äúperverse instantiation‚Äù. Getting into more general economic, behavioral, or human situations would be going too far afield, but the relevant analogues are ‚Äú principal-agent problem ‚Å† ‚Äù, ‚Äú perverse incentives ‚Å† ‚Äù, ‚Äúlaw of unintended consequences ‚Å† ‚Äù, ‚Äú Lucas critique ‚Å† ‚Äù, ‚Äú Goodhart‚Äôs law ‚Å† ‚Äù, or ‚Äú Campbell‚Äôs law ‚Å† ‚Äù; such alignment problems are only partially dealt with by having ground-truth evolutionary ‚Äòouter‚Äô losses ‚Å† , and avoiding reward hacking remains an open problem (even in theory). Speedrun ‚Å† gaming communities frequently provide examples of reward-hacking, particularly when games are finished faster by exploiting bugs to sequence break ‚Å† ; particularly esoteric techniques require outright hacking the ‚Å†‚Äúweird machines‚Äù ‚Å† present in many games/ devices‚Äîfor example, pannenkoek2012‚Äôs ‚Å† ‚Å†‚Äòparallel universes‚Äô ‚Å† Super Mario 64 ‚Å† hack which ‚Å†avoids using any jumps ‚Å† by exploiting an integer overflow ‚Å† bug & modulo ‚Å† wraparound to accelerate Mario to near-infinite speed, passing through the entire map multiple times, in order to stop at the right place. Perhaps people can make suggestions, but a few examples I have found or recall include‚Ä¶

Guerrilla warfare‚Äôs ‚Å† effectiveness is its own topic; we can note that many of the same cognitive biases ‚Å† like the availability heuristic ‚Å† that skew our beliefs on terrorism also apply to guerrilla warfare as well‚Äîeveryone remembers the successful American Revolution, but who ever invokes the ‚Å†scores or hundreds ‚Å† of other revolts & failed revolutions in the British Empire which involved guerrilla tactics? (Or in the American empire ‚Å† , for that matter‚Äîeg. Shays‚Äô Rebellion ‚Å† , the Whiskey rebellion ‚Å† , or Nat Turner ‚Å† ? How well did the American South succeed in seceding, in a conflict with quite as many irregular forces as the American Revolution?) Does a close examination of the Vietnam War ‚Å† , where the much-heralded Vietcong ‚Å† were destroyed after the Tet Offensive ‚Å† and before the North Vietnamese army ‚Å† crushed the ARVN and conquered South Vietnam, reveal it to have been more effective than conventional warfare? A cursory look through any somewhat comprehensive ‚Å† list of guerrilla movements does not reveal it to be a list of luminaries. ‚ÄúNobody likes a loser‚Äù, least of all in war. But to return to terrorism.

Many configuration or special-purpose languages or tools or complicated games turn out to violate the Rule of least power ‚Å† & be ‚Å†‚Äúaccidentally Turing-complete‚Äù , like ‚Å†Sendmail ‚Å† ‚Å† ‚Å†1‚Å† , ‚Å†MediaWiki templates , ‚Å†sed or repeated regexp/ find-replace commands ‚Å† in an editor (any form of string substitution ‚Å† or templating or compile-time computation is highly likely to be TC on its own or when iterated since they often turn out to support a lambda calculus ‚Å† or a term-rewriting ‚Å† language or tag system eg. esolangs ‚Å†‚Äú/// ‚Äù or ‚Å†Thue ), XSLT ‚Å† , ‚Å†Infinite Minesweeper ‚Å† , ‚Å†Dwarf ‚Å†Fortress ‚Å† ‚Å†2‚Å† , Starcraft, Minecraft ‚Å† , Ant ‚Å† , ‚Å†Transport ‚Å†Tycoon & ‚Å†Cities: Skyline , C++ templates ‚Å† & Java generics ‚Å† , RNA ‚Å† / DNA computing ‚Å† etc are TC but these are not surprising either: many games support scripting (ie. TC-ness) to make their development easier and enable fan modifications, so games‚Äô TC may be as simple as including syntax for calling out to a better-known language like Perl, or it may just be an obscure part of a standard format (most people these days are probably unaware that TrueType ‚Å† & many fonts are PostScript ‚Å† programs based on stack machines, similar to ‚Å†DWARF debugging and ELF metadata , or that some music formats ‚Å† go beyond MIDI ‚Å† in providing scripting capabilities and must be interpreted to be displayed; once one knows this, then fonts being TC are no more surprising than T eX documents being TC, leading of course, to many severe & fascinating font or media security vulnerabilities such as ‚Å†the BLEND vulnerability ‚Å† or ‚Å†SNES & ‚Å†NES code exploiting Linux systems . Other formats, like PDF, are simply appalling.).

Bugs

CANTFIX:

  • Browser search highlights: when using in-page search in a web browser ( C-f), highlighted text or links or other text elements may look ugly (often due to the text-shadow trick used for underlining).

    These cannot be fixed because the highlighting of search results is done by the web browser, and is inaccessible to the website JS/ CSS.

    The only fix that might work is dropping the text-shadow trick entirely in favor of the CSS skip-ink feature, but that is supported by too few browsers & current implementations are typographically inferior (failing at their one & only job).

    • Interaction with collapses: there is a bug when searching for text in a page, when the text is within a collapsed section. The found text will be revealed‚Äîbut only after the user cancels out of the find-in-page UI; it won‚Äôt be revealed while the search UI (triggered by ‚ÄúFind‚Äù and then typing, or hitting the ‚ÄúFind Next‚Äù shortcut) is open.

      This is not possible to fix given current browser implementations. (And probably not ever, because of spurious ‚Äúprivacy‚Äù concerns in the specification.)

  • Firefox Ligatures: sometimes a ligature will be ‚Äòsplit‚Äô across multiple lines ( ‚Å†example ‚Å† ), looking oddly buggy.

    This is a long-standing (since 2009 15ya ) ‚Å†Firefox bug ‚Å† in its font rendering code, and cannot be fixed in any way other than disabling ligatures entirely.

WONTFIX:

  • No RSS Feed: there is no on-site RSS feed.

    This is because Gwern.net is not a blog & I do not write in small discrete finished units published regularly, so RSS feeds don‚Äôt map well‚ÄîI provided for years a RSS feed of Git ‚Å† revisions, but it was never useful. Manually curating RSS items would be a pain, and going further to provide RSS feeds for every little thing like per-directory file creations would be even more of a pain (particularly given the increasing difficulty of doing anything complicated in Hakyll).

    The monthly Substack ‚Å† newsletters provide an RSS feed, and for the private / r/ gwern subreddit, one can create a Reddit search for the flair:Gwern & Reddit should provide an (authenticated) RSS feed for that.

Radiance ‚Å† Carter Scholz 2003 ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ

(Quotes are extracted from my annotated ebook edition of Radiance ‚Å† ; see also my ‚Å†list of other review ‚Å† & ‚Å†excerpts from them ‚Å† .)

Publisher summary:

Somewhere in California, in the 1990s, a nuclear weapons lab develops advanced technologies for its post-Cold War mission. Advanced as in not working yet. Mission as in continued funding. A scandal-plagued missile defense program presses forward, dragging physicist Philip Quine deep into the machinations of those who would use the lab for their own gain.

      Dwarf Fortress provides clockwork mechanisms, so TC is unsurprising; but the water is implemented as a simple cellular automation, so there might be more ways of getting TC in DF! The DF wiki currently lists 4 potential ways of creating logic gates: the fluids, the clockwork mechanisms, mine-carts, and creature/ animal logic gates involving doors+pressure-sensors.
